"`world/collisions` returns a list of colliding entity pairs each
frame. Reading it well is 90% of your collision-handling code. Reading
it badly = crashes, double-hits, missed events, and performance
cliffs.

This appendix teaches the patterns that scale.

## The naive walk

```scheme
(for-each
 (lambda (pair)
   (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
     ;; handle a and b
     ))
 (world/collisions))
```

Works. Two problems:

1. The pair may appear in either order — sometimes (a=player, b=coin),
   sometimes (a=coin, b=player). You need to handle both.
2. If a and b are the same entity across multiple pairs in one frame
   (e.g. player collided with 3 coins), you handle three times.
   Usually fine, sometimes not.

## Pattern 1 — normalize order

Ensure a is always the 'lower-kind' or 'lower-id' partner.

```scheme
(define (normalize-pair pair)
  (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
    (if (symbol<? (entity/kind a) (entity/kind b))
        (list a b)
        (list b a))))
```

Or by ID:
```scheme
(define (normalize-pair-by-id pair)
  (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
    (if (< (entity/id a) (entity/id b))
        (list a b)
        (list b a))))
```

Then normalize each pair before dispatching. Simplifies the handler
code — you only handle one order.

## Pattern 2 — dispatch by kind

Group handlers by (kind-a, kind-b) pair.

```scheme
(define collision-handlers
  '((player   coin)  handle-player-coin
    (player   enemy) handle-player-enemy
    (bullet   enemy) handle-bullet-enemy))

(define (dispatch pair)
  (let ((k1 (entity/kind (car pair)))
        (k2 (entity/kind (cadr pair))))
    (let loop ((table collision-handlers))
      (cond
        ((null? table) #f)
        ((and (eq? (caar table) k1) (eq? (cadar table) k2))
         ((cadr table) (car pair) (cadr pair)))
        (else (loop (cddr table)))))))
```

Cleaner than nested `cond`. Every pair-kind gets exactly one handler.
Order-normalize the pair first.

## Pattern 3 — dedupe by frame

Only handle each (a-id, b-id) once per frame.

```scheme
(define handled-this-frame '())

(define (once-per-frame-handler pair)
  (let* ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair))
         (key (list (entity/id a) (entity/id b))))
    (unless (member key handled-this-frame)
      (set! handled-this-frame (cons key handled-this-frame))
      (dispatch pair))))

;; At end of frame:
(set! handled-this-frame '())
```

Prevents double-firing for the same collision pair (which can happen
when the runtime returns both orders).

## Pattern 4 — alive guard

Check entities are still alive before handling.

```scheme
(for-each
 (lambda (pair)
   (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
     (when (and (entity/alive? a) (entity/alive? b))
       (dispatch pair))))
 (world/collisions))
```

A collision may have despawned one partner in an earlier pair this
frame. Trying to process it again = null-pointer.

## Pattern 5 — early-exit on player death

Player died; skip the rest of the frame's collisions.

```scheme
(let ((player-alive? #t))
  (for-each
   (lambda (pair)
     (when player-alive?
       (when (kind-in-pair pair 'player)
         (dispatch-player-collision pair))
       (unless (entity/alive? (find-player))
         (set! player-alive? #f))))
   (world/collisions)))
```

Prevents 'player died 5 times in one frame' bugs.

## Pattern 6 — sort by team

For many-vs-many, group collisions by team.

```scheme
(let ((team-a-hits 0) (team-b-hits 0))
  (for-each
   (lambda (pair)
     (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
       (cond
         ((and (eq? (entity/team a) 'a) (eq? (entity/team b) 'b))
          (set! team-a-hits (+ team-a-hits 1)))
         ((and (eq? (entity/team a) 'b) (eq? (entity/team b) 'a))
          (set! team-b-hits (+ team-b-hits 1))))))
   (world/collisions))
  ...)
```

Tally, then apply. Prevents ordering bias.

## Pattern 7 — cost accounting

Count how many pairs your frame handles.

```scheme
(let ((count (length (world/collisions))))
  (when (> count 100)
    (display \"Warning: high collision count \")
    (display count) (newline)))
```

If count grows into the thousands, you have a layer problem — too
many entities share too permissive a layer. Split layers, or use
sensors instead of solids for pass-through cases.

## Big-O in kid terms

The runtime uses spatial hashing to keep collision cost near O(n)
in the number of ACTUAL collisions, not O(n^2) in entity count. So:

- 100 entities that don't overlap: ~100 hash lookups per frame.
  Trivial.
- 100 entities all overlapping: 100 * 100 / 2 = 5000 collision
  pairs. Might drop from 60 to 55 FPS at kid-scale hardware.
- 1000 entities with normal spread: still O(1000-ish). Fine.
- 1000 entities all overlapping: catastrophic.

The lesson: layers + sensors + smart level design (entities spread
out) matter more than iterating 'efficiently.'

## Common desktop tasks

**Duplicate-order detection.** A shop's checkout flow needs to know
if a customer clicked 'submit' twice in one second (accidental
double-buy). Same dedupe pattern as collision de-double-hit.

## Debugging with world/collisions

Print every pair for one frame to see what's actually colliding.

```scheme
(define (debug-print-collisions)
  (for-each
   (lambda (pair)
     (display (entity/kind (car pair)))
     (display \" hit \")
     (display (entity/kind (cadr pair)))
     (newline))
   (world/collisions)))
```

Call once from `on-frame` (guarded by a debug flag). See what your
world is doing. Usually reveals a layer bug or a shape-oversize bug.

## The final rule

If your collision code is more than 30 lines, it's probably wrong.
Layers + normalized dispatch + alive-guard should cover 95% of
arcade games. If you have branching per-kind with 20 arms and
nested conditionals, split it into small handlers by kind-pair.")
